    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_981185042" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/981185042" />
    <a title="Jon" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/22486050-jon"><img alt="Jon" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1414880210p2/22486050.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/981185042?book_show_action=true">Jun 29, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jon" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jon" href="/user/show/22486050-jon">Jon</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/12923448-the-wolf-s-hour">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer981185042" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6088080582566533897"><i>The Wolf’s Hour</i> is, essentially, two stories. In fact, I’d go as far as to argue that this novel may well have started out as two completely separate ideas, before being forcibly merged together into its final form. I have absolutely no concrete evidence to support my (admittedly rather tenuous) claim, but at some point over the course of this review I’ll try to explain why I think this may be the case.<br/><br/>The principal plot thread sees our hero, Michael Gallatin (born and raised in Russia as Mikhai</span>
  <span id="freeText6088080582566533897" style="display:none"><i>The Wolf’s Hour</i> is, essentially, two stories. In fact, I’d go as far as to argue that this novel may well have started out as two completely separate ideas, before being forcibly merged together into its final form. I have absolutely no concrete evidence to support my (admittedly rather tenuous) claim, but at some point over the course of this review I’ll try to explain why I think this may be the case.<br /><br />The principal plot thread sees our hero, Michael Gallatin (born and raised in Russia as Mikhail Gallatinov, and now - after a slight name change - a British secret agent) race across war torn Nazi-occupied Europe, as he tries to unravel the mystery of ‘Iron Fist’; a super-weapon that threatens the success of the Allies’ D-Day offensive. But Michael also has a hidden ace up his sleeve: not only is he a super-special, super-secret agent, he’s also a <i>werewolf</i>. I bet you didn’t see <i>that</i> coming. He’s the epitome of the ‘alpha male’: rugged and daring; strong, brave and eye-wateringly handsome. The bitches love him. As do the <i>human</i> females. <i>Ahem</i>. He’s basically James Bond and Rin Tin Tin, all rolled into one.<br /><br />I honestly thought this was going to be a parody. I really, really <i>hoped</i> it was going to be a parody, because I don’t see how anyone could take the above premise at all seriously. Sadly, McCammon plays it as straight as he possibly can, and the plot descends into a comic book farce with ridiculously over-the-top Nazi villain stereotypes, including (but not limited to) the <i>mad doctor</i>; the <i>cold, calculating colonel</i> (whose arrogance and overconfidence leads him to reveal the details of his dastardly plan, of course); his <i>brutish, tank-like bodyguard</i>; and a <i>psychopathic big-game hunter/assassin</i>. In addition, we’re also treated to <i>the attractive (and very forward) lady resistance fighter</i>, and <i>the beautiful double agent</i> (who also just happens to be a famous actress). Even Hitler turns up, in a scene that seemed like it came straight out of a Mel Brooks movie.<br /><br />Fortunately, we have the promise of some lycanthropy action to relieve the ho-hum mundanity of the plot, surely? Actually, not really. During the WWII action-adventure part of the story, Michael only ever really transforms (because he can transform at will, of course - none of that old-fashioned full moon tomfoolery here) as a means of escaping seemingly ‘inescapable’ situations: the werewolf is really only used as a plot-device to write the protagonist out of a corner.<br /><br />However, as mentioned, this is a novel of two stories. The second, and, in my opinion, easily better story, tells the tale of young Mikhail; orphaned during the Russian revolution and ‘adopted’ by a pack of werewolves. We follow Mikhail through the years as he grows to adulthood, living in the Russian wilderness and learning to understand the laws of nature that govern the lives of his new family. These sections do, quite frankly, verge on being utterly brilliant - but do not gel seamlessly with the rest of the novel.<br /><br />There’s very little overlap between the two stories, and the references that are occasionally made to Michael’s past life feel rather forced and at odds with the rest of the prose. It’s a shame, because McCammon’s writing is never poor; he knows how to make the chapters flow and, as such, this was a very easy read. But there were far too many cringe-worthy moments for me to find this book anything above passable.<br /><br />I’ll certainly try McCammon again, but fans of Jack Higgins or Ian Fleming are probably going to get much more out of this particular novel than I did.</span>
  <a data-text-id="6088080582566533897" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


