    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3168408511" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3168408511" />
    <a title="Warren Fournier" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/56665940-warren-fournier"><img alt="Warren Fournier" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1621886976p2/56665940.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3168408511?book_show_action=true">Jan 30, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Warren Fournier" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Warren Fournier" href="/user/show/56665940-warren-fournier">Warren Fournier</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/56665940-warren-fournier?shelf=horror-paperbacks-from-70s-to-90s">horror-paperbacks-from-70s-to-90s</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3168408511" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2863712205857110757">I am not one of those guys that gives high ratings to any horror novel because it&apos;s got werewolves or vampires in it. I don&apos;t particularly gravitate to those sorts of creature features. But occasionally, there are novels that put a really neat twist on the subgenres. &quot;Carrion Comfort&quot; and &quot;Necroscope&quot; turned vampire lore on its head. And &quot;Wolf&apos;s Hour&quot; did the same for the werewolf story.<br/><br/>This is pure genius, as McCammon achieved a near impossible feat by combining so many elements into an effecti</span>
  <span id="freeText2863712205857110757" style="display:none">I am not one of those guys that gives high ratings to any horror novel because it's got werewolves or vampires in it. I don't particularly gravitate to those sorts of creature features. But occasionally, there are novels that put a really neat twist on the subgenres. "Carrion Comfort" and "Necroscope" turned vampire lore on its head. And "Wolf's Hour" did the same for the werewolf story.<br /><br />This is pure genius, as McCammon achieved a near impossible feat by combining so many elements into an effective and exciting historical thriller. At heart, the novel is a superhero action thriller, but with a supernatural twist, and with a peppering of romance, drama, and comedy. Many have tried such experiments and failed, as the result is a muddled mess that doesn't know what it wants to be and pleases no one. Not so with "Wolf's Hour."<br /><br />The pace will leave you breathless, and you are in genuine suspense because the threats are based on the very real evil that humans are capable of doing rather than some outlandish and contorted paranormal plot that risks taking you out of the story. And even though the main protagonist is a werewolf, he is written with depth and compassion, feeling very real and likeable while struggling with a dark side. He is far from another wooden pulp hero, being more "The Hulk" than "Superman." His adventures become exhausting through this lengthy volume, but you are left feeling happy with your workout at the end. <br /><br />More exciting and satisfying than most movies of its ilk, McCammon shows us just what literature can do. It may not be everyone's cup of tea, but if you are a horror or thriller fan, you should seek this out.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2863712205857110757" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

